We recommended that Management:
Require the implementing office, in coordination with Bid and Awards Committee (BAC) and Budget Office, to review the reasonableness of PPAs costing to preclude series of failure of bidding, thus expedite the procurement activities and reducing the risk of delayed or non-implementation;
Require the Municipal Accountant, to continue to prioritize the accurate and timely recognition of the LDRRM fund prior years’ unexpended balances. Accordingly, the MDRRMO, to ensure timely consensus with the MDRRM Council relative to the allocation of these balances to identified PPAs. Henceforth, ensure operationalization of the identified PPAs during the year by supplemental budget and for subsequent approval of the Sangguniang Bayan through an ordinance, thus, optimal utilization of LDRRM funds can be achieved;
Discontinue the utilization of LDRRM funds for activities or events that do not align with the primary purpose of addressing disaster-related needs of the LGU. Accordingly, the MDRRMO, shall maintain a monitoring of the supplies prepositioned to the implementing offices and conduct a periodic review and validation of its utilization;
Require the implementing office, in coordination with BAC, to adopt a more dynamic procurement strategy aligned with weather forecasts and historical data on weather patterns in the locality to ensure the sufficiency and immediate availability of LDRRM-related items, when needed. Accordingly, for welfare food items, Management shall endeavor to enter into Framework Agreement with prospective suppliers and “Call-off” may be executed and issued to the winning supplier immediately upon the determination that an item is needed, pursuant to the guidelines under Annex 32 of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (RIRR) of Republic Act (RA) No. 9184 otherwise known as the Government Procurement Reform Act. With this, lean and just-in-time procurements are achieved and the limited storage facilities of the LGU can be maximized;
Utilize the stock card in the inventory management to ensure that welfare goods are available and in optimal condition when required. Similarly, ensure the timely and proper disposal of nearly expiring goods/items through the identified modality by the LGU, to preclude any wastage of government funds; and
Ensure that all properties of the government are properly safeguarded against deterioration, loss and wastage.

We recommended that Management:
Intensify the procurement planning by conducting trend analysis to determine activity requirements specifically on the meals and snacks and consider entering into a Framework Agreement, as allowed in Appendix 32, 2016 RIRR of RA No. 9184 following the procedures for competitive bidding;
Adopt the implementation of EPA for the public bidding on the procurement of meals and snacks under a Framework Agreement to cover annually recuring activities such as Management Committee meetings, quarterly meetings of Gender and Development (GAD) Committee, and other similar activities determinable by Management;
Refrain from the practice of reimbursement of representation expenses except for exceptional cases such as: (a) Section 53.2 Negotiated Procurement thru Emergency Cases and (b) Per diems in connection to official travels; and
Ensure that procurement of meals and snacks are included in the concerned office’s PPMP and ultimately the agency’s Annual Procurement Plan (APP) and the proof of which shall be attached to the disbursement vouchers.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments as members and completely conduct physical count of Inventory of the Municipality’s PPE annually and submit to the Office of the Auditor the duly accomplished RPCPPE of all PPE accounts;
To direct the Municipal Accountant and designated General Services Officer reconcile and analyze the difference between ledger and RPCPPE report and effect necessary adjustments;
Instruct the General Services Office to transfer all identified unserviceable properties in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) Form as prescribed in Annex 51, Volume 2 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, for proper disposal and basis to derecognize from the book of accounts, then undertake necessary actions for disposal in accordance with Section 79 of PD 1445;
To require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO-Designate maintain Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELC) and Property Cards for each group of PPEs, respectively and reconciliation between these two records shall be undertaken regularly; and
In response to COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, create an Inventory Committee for the sole purpose of conducting a one-time cleansing of the Municipality’s PPE which shall be composed of adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory.

Conduct investigation on beginning balances of the Due to NGAs account to determine its nature, specific purpose and the source agency from which the funds were received. Thereafter, facilitate evaluation to determine whether the corresponding projects have been implemented and return the unused funds to the source agency, if warranted;
Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer cause the refund of the excess amount of completed projects and idle/unutilized amount to the concerned SAs in compliance with COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 13, 1994 and with the MOA; and
Effect proper adjustments for deficiencies noted and errors uncovered to reflect the correct account balances.

Require the BAC to undergo procurement process in hiring consultants;

Submit reports on the LGU’s situation during the time of hiring the consultants with specific details which gives rise to the necessity of hiring the consultants;
Submit specific and justifiable Consultancy Progress Reports or any form of accomplishment report for each month of CY 2022 to check whether the purpose for hiring consultants were actually achieved for further verification;

Submit copies of Professional License or Curriculum Vitae or any proof that BAC had evaluate the qualifications and expertise of the hired consultants;

All contracts and each of all documents forming part thereof should be submitted to the Office of the Auditor within five calendar days from the date of execution.

