2.The LCE direct the Municipal Assessor̕ s Office to exert effort in titling the land owned by the Municipality;


3.The LCE require the Accounting Office to set up and maintain complete accounting records; 

4.The LCE require the Treasurer̕ s Office/GSO to keep on file complete records of real properties; and,

5.The LCE direct the Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of all the parcels of land owned by the Municipality and reconcile with the books for proper presentation in the FS.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:


   1. Reorganize Inventory Committee and mobilize competent and  responsible personnel as members of the Inventory Committee to completely  conduct physical count of the Municipality’s PPE annually, prepare reports and to submit the duly accomplished RPCPPE to the Auditor;

   2. Direct  the  Municipal  Accountant  and  designated  General  Services Officer to religiously maintain the  PPELC  and  Stock  Cards/Property Cards;

   3. Direct  the  Municipal  Accountant  and  designated  General  Services Officer  to  reconcile  and  analyze  the  difference  between   their respective offices and effect necessary adjustments; and

   4. Instruct the  General  Services  Office  to  transfer  all  identified unserviceable properties in the Inventory  and  Inspection  Report  of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) Form as prescribed in Annex 51,  Volume 2 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, for proper disposal and basis to derecognize from  the  book  of  accounts,  then  undertake  necessary actions for disposal in accordance with Section 79 of PD 1445.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:


   1. Require all drivers to  prepare  a  Driver’s  Trip  Tickets  with  all information  required  properly  supplied  and  a  Monthly  Report  of Official Travel for each Vehicle;


   2. See to it that requisitioning  officer  accomplish  and  have  a  duly approved RIV or equivalent as a basis of procuring fuel and lubricants from a gasoline service station;


   3. Prepare a monthly fuel consumption report and a  submit  copy  to  the auditor within the first 10 days of the following month; and


   4. The Municipal Accounting Office cautiously review the completeness  of the attached supporting documents in  allowing  the  payment  of  fuel consumption.

We recommended Management to:
require the PEO to furnish the PGSO and PAccO a complete and accurate list of all ongoing projects including the summary of materials issued per project;
direct the PGSO, based on the list to be furnished by the PEO, to retrieve the Purchase Orders, Acceptance and Inspection Reports and other pertinent documents for each of the projects identified and establish a monitoring thereon;
require the PAccO and the PGSO to reconcile their records and make the necessary adjustments on the records based on verifiable information and supporting documents, as necessary, to establish the correct balance of the inventory account;
require the PAccO to determine the actual status of the construction materials for prior year projects for possible write-down of the inventories to net realizable value, where circumstances permit; and
determine, in case of loss, deterioration, or obsolescence of the inventories due to negligence, the appropriate action on the employees who may be found liable thereon.
During the exit conference, the Provincial Governor instructed the Provincial Engineer to conduct an inventory and prepare a list of all ongoing construction projects implemented “by Administration”. All offices concerned were also advised to reconcile their records. Management committed to implement our recommendations.

We recommended that Management:
create a committee that will rigorously pursue the collection of prior year receivables from the identified accountable officers/debtors. Relative to this, Management shall exhaust all possible efforts to collect the receivables such as, but not limited to instituting legal actions against delinquent borrowers, as applicable;
instruct the Provincial Accountant to conduct a thorough assessment, evaluation and investigation of the outstanding accounts and record impairment and other adjustments thereof;
direct the Provincial Accountant to review the status of the receivables and observe the guidelines and procedures on the write-off of Dormant Receivable accounts as prescribed in COA Circular 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and
require the Provincial Accountant to analyze and investigate the nature of the items with negative balances in the Receivable accounts and prepare the proper entries to reclassify them to liability accounts, as appropriate and henceforth, observe the proper presentation of Receivable accounts in the financial statements.
Management committed to comply with our recommendations. At present, a committee is in place to monitor the collection on newly-issued loans. Management shall create a similar committee to enforce collection on the long outstanding receivable.

We recommended that Management:
require the Provincial Accountant and the Provincial Engineer to investigate the difference on the cost of the 48 fully completed projects amounting to P25,182,584.71. The Accounting Office shall adjust the books based on sufficient and verifiable evidence and transfer to the appropriate accounts the cost thereof;
direct the Provincial Accountant, the Provincial Engineer and Agency’s Inspectorate Team to conduct an inventory on all the ongoing projects and reconcile the differences noted in the records of the two offices;
advise the Provincial Engineer to issue Certificate of Completion after careful evaluation and inspection of each successfully completed project and transmit the same to the Accounting Office for proper recording; and
ensure that the records of the two offices are reconciled regularly to avoid misleading information on the status of the agency’s construction projects.
Management assured compliance on our recommendations. Relative to this, a comprehensive inventory of all the ongoing projects shall be spearheaded by the PEO to determine their status. According to Management, it will improve its reporting systems to ensure that all documents that are necessary in the recording of transactions relative to ongoing projects are transmitted promptly to the Accounting Office to avoid unreconciled amounts.

We recommended that Management:
continue with the ongoing physical count, prepare the complete report thereon and submit the same to the Auditor’s Office;
henceforth, schedule the annual physical count as close as practicable to December 31 of each year. Relative to this, strict monitoring and control shall be made for the issuances and procurement from the actual date of the count to the December 31 cut-off date for inclusion in the final report to be submitted on or before January 31 of the ensuing year;
instruct the Provincial Accountant to identify the cause of the negative balance in the “Military and Police Equipment” account, prepare appropriate adjusting entries, as warranted and submit a copy thereof to the Auditor’s Office; and
review and strictly enforce the documentary and procedural requirements of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of Government Agencies.
During the exit conference, the Chairman of the Inventory Committee informed that Audit Team that they are finalizing the RPCPPE. The Audit Team was assured that the actual physical count shall be scheduled before year-end so that the related report will be submitted on time. Management also signified its intention to implement the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances as prescribed in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that Management:
require the focal persons for the projects identified to locate all available documents to support the unliquidated fund transfers and submit the same to the Accounting Office to facilitate the updating of the records;
require the employees responsible in implementing the PPAs covered by the fund transfers to determine the status of implementation thereof, prepare a liquidation report and submit to the Accounting Office;
based on the documents to be submitted by the focal persons, direct the Accounting Office to update the schedules and supply the details such as source agency, date of grant and number of years outstanding and furnish a copy thereof to the Audit Team;
based on the updated information, initiate an inquiry with the identified Source Agencies as regards the balances in their books and request a certification thereof duly signed by the Agency Accountant and the Head of the Agency;
instruct the Provincial Accountant to conduct a thorough assessment, evaluation and investigation of the outstanding accounts and record adjustments thereof;
direct the Provincial Accountant to review the status of the accounts and observe the guidelines and procedures on the write-off of Dormant Payable accounts as prescribed in COA Circular 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;
require the Provincial Accountant to evaluate he nature of the payables and reclassify the P2,668,593.89 from “Due to NGAs” to “Due to GOCCs”, as appropriate; and
require the Provincial Accountant to analyze and investigate the nature of the items with negative balances in the Due to National Government Agencies account and prepare the proper entries to reclassify them to receivable accounts, as appropriate and henceforth, observe the proper presentation of “Due to NGAs” accounts in the financial statements.
During the exit conference, Management committed to comply with our recommendations.

We recommended that Management:
direct the property custodians in various offices to submit immediately the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) to the PGSO for recording purposes;
require the PGSO to cause the immediate retrieval of all supplies and materials under the custody of the end-user units and maintain a centralized inventory management system. Relative to this, the PGSO personnel to be assigned in the preparation of SSMI shall submit the report to the Accounting Office on a weekly basis;
direct the Provincial General Services Officer and other PGSO and PEO personnel directly involved in the control and management of supplies and properties to apply for a fidelity bond with the Bureau of the Treasury;
require the Agency’s Inventory Committee together with the representatives from the PEO and PGSO to conduct an inventory count and tagging on all the accumulated excess construction materials from the projects implemented in the prior years and effect a proper turn-over thereon;
identify the appropriate programs, projects and activities to which the excess construction materials from projects in prior years may be used and propose the same to the Sangguniang Panlalawigan for appropriate approval. Accordingly, the disposition of the said materials shall be properly monitored and controlled;
direct the PGSO to maintain a record of all construction materials on a per project basis, a report on the balance thereon shall be prepared upon the issuance of the PEO of the Certificate of Completion for each successfully completed project; and
require the immediate stockpiling/warehousing of the construction materials that are directly exposed to extreme weather conditions and ensure that all properties of the government are properly safeguarded against deterioration, loss and wastage.
We were informed during the exit conference that concerned offices have been instructed to submit their respective SSMIs. The physical count of the accumulated excess construction materials is ongoing and the custodians have applied for fidelity bond with the BTr. Management committed to implement our recommendations.

We recommended that Management:
advise the Provincial Planning and Development Coordinator (PPDC) together with the concerned implementing offices, in coordination with the Bids and Awards Committee, to immediately look into the unimplemented under the 20% Development Fund and determine causes of their non-implementation, as the case may be. Formulate/develop specific strategies/solutions to effectively implement development projects. Consider formulating a timetable within which to complete the projects and review the costing of projects programmed two to seven years ago to conform to the present conditions;
require the Accounting Office and the Office of the Provincial Planning and Development Coordinator to investigate the differences in the reports of the two offices and henceforth ensure that their reports are correct, up-to-date and reconciled;
direct the offices concerned to vigorously pursue the completion of the projects to be implemented the soonest time possible in order to achieve the objectives of providing socio-economic benefits to the intended beneficiaries;
require the PEO to improve the planning and scheduling of work activities and manpower in order to facilitate completion of the Program of Work of unimplemented projects. Ensure that plans are accurate and projects estimates are based on standard and realistic amounts; and
advise the PPDC to enhance monitoring of implementation of projects in coordination with the implementing offices and to submit regularly status reports of implementation to the Provincial Governor for her information so that appropriate measures can be instituted to obtain optimal utilization of fund.

We recommended that Management:
require the Chairman of the Bids and Awards Committee to explain/justify with verifiable basis why disbursements on procurements which were noted as non-compliant with existing procurement law and the COA rules and regulations, as mentioned above, should not be suspended/disallowed in post-audit;
advise the BAC to revisit the procedures and guidelines for all modalities of procurement and identify the most appropriate mode for each procurement project;
henceforth, carefully review all requests for time extension and avoid approving more than the maximum allowable period;
require the BAC Secretariat to utilize the latest standard format of bidding documents and required forms prescribed by the GPPB. Accordingly, Management shall endeavor to monitor the latest issuances of the GPPB affecting the form and contents of the bidding documents;
advise the end-users and the BAC Secretariat to indicate the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC) and properly fill out the Requests for Quotations (RFQs) with the required information; and
ensure that the posting requirements are complied with and the proof thereof are attached to the disbursement vouchers to establish the correctness of information and reliability of the procurement process.
The representative of the BAC, during the exit conference assured compliance with our audit observations. The BAC including the Secretariat and Technical Working Group shall convene to review the forms and bidding documents currently being used for updating. Also, Management informed the Audit Team of the stricter rules to be observed in approving time extensions. On the other hand, the internet connectivity issue is a major factor cited in the non-compliance to the posting requirements.

